object-02.text: GROSS FEATURES OF SELECTED PHILIPPINE WOOD SPECIES

object-04.text:
Objectives of the Learning Object

1. review with the gross features of selected Philippine wood species, and

2. identify these species on the basis of its gross features.

object-08.text: Supervisor Vic is orienting their newly hired Forester, Sue.

object-09.text: Hi Sue! Welcome to your first day at work.

object-10.text: I will assign you at the checkpoint today. You need to verify the identity of the logs harvested and transported by different logging companies and collect the corresponding forest charges.

object-11.text: We will look at the gross features of wood, specifically its physical and structural features.

object-12.text: But before deployment, let us go to our xylarium to review these physical and structural features of some Philippine wood species.

object-13.text: Well noted, Sir. Reviewing these features will be very helpful to me in the smooth performance of my task. Let me just get my things and I will follow you in the xylarium.

object-15.text:
Physical and Structural

Features

of Selected Philippine

Wood Species

object-17.text: If you will recall, physical features are those features that can be perceived by the senses and can be observed even without the use of a hand lens, while structural features refer to the cellular make up of the wood.

object-18.text: We will focus more on the structural features since these are more reliable bases for identification.

object-19.text: We also need to take note of the distinct features of each species to help facilitate species identification.

object-20.text: Let us examine selected species under the family Fabaceae. We will start with AYANGILE, *Acacia confusa*

object-22.text:
Ayangile's distinct features are:

Its brownish black color, moderately numerous pores that are moderately small, presence of white deposits and vasicentric parenchyma.

object-25.text:
Batete's distinct features are:

Its reddish-brown color, moderately numerous pores that are moderately large and  parenchyma types are boundary, aliform, aliform confluent, and vasicentric. It has yellow and white deposits, and diffuse oil ducts.

object-28.text:
Golden shower's distinct features are:

Its reddish brown to brick red color, moderately numerous and moderately large pores, presence of red deposits and banded confluent parenchyma.

object-31.text:
Kakauate's distinct features are:

The profuse presence of tyloses and banded confluent parenchyma.

object-34.text:
Logwood's distinct features are:

Its light to dark brown color, moderately numerous solitary pores that are small, presence of white deposits and aliform confluent parenchyma.

object-35.text: Now, Sue, are you ready to go to the checkpoint? I think the truck scheduled for today's inspection is arriving real soon.

object-36.text: Yes Sir, Thank you very much. I will head now to the checkpoint.

object-38.text: Sue went to the checkpoint and waited for the truck to arrive. She tried to recall all the features that they reviewed.

object-39.text: While waiting, she decided to review the other species.

object-41.text: Sue clicks on NARRA, *Pterocarpus indicus* forma indicus.

object-42.text:
Narra's distinct features are:

Its pale yellow to dark reddish-brown color, ring-porous topography, long aliform confluent and presence of ripple marks.

object-45.text:
Siar's distinct features are:

Its whitish brown to light brown color, moderately few small pores, boundary parenchyma and presence of ripple marks.

object-47.text: Sue clicks on RAIN TREE, *Samanea saman*

object-48.text:
Rain tree's distinct features are:

Its whitish or brownish color, moderately few pores that are moderately small to moderately large, thick vasicentric parenchyma and mostyle solitary pores.

object-50.text: Sue heard the sound of an approaching truck loaded with logs.

object-54.text: Good day, Sir. It seems that you travelled a long distance. I hope that you had a safe travel. As a matter of protocol, may I see your transportation permit.

object-56.text: Ma'am, it's been indeed a long travel. Here is our transportation permit.

object-57.text: Wait for a while Sir as I inspect the load.

object-58.text:
Sue inspected the permit and took note of the species listed in the permit.

These are Supa, Moluccan sau, Akle, Manggis and Banuyo.

object-60.text:
Sue inspected the first log and noted the following characteristics:

It has yellowish red to chestnut brown color with black streaks, numerous small pores, with boundary parenchyma and concentric oil ducts.

object-61.text: These characteristics match that of SUPA, *Sindora supa*.

object-63.text:
She inspected the next log and noted the following characteristics:

It has white, pale pink to light reddish color, few moderately large solitary pores, vasicentric parenchyma and narrow wood rays.

object-64.text: These characteristics match that of MOLUCCAN SAU, *Paraserianthes falcataria*.

object-66.text:
She inspected the next log and noted the following characteristics:

It has dark brown color, pores are moderately few and moderately small to moderately large, presence of yellow, red and black deposits, aliform and aliform confluent parenchyma.

object-67.text: These characteristics match that of AKLE, *Albizia acle*.

object-69.text:
She inspected the next log and noted the following characteristics:

It is light red to cacao red in color, pores are moderately few and are large to large in size, with vasicentric and concentric parenchyma and ripple marks.

object-70.text: These characteristics match that of MANGGIS, *Koompassia excelsa*.

object-72.text:
She inspected the next log and noted the following characteristics:

It has light golden brown color, pores are moderately small and moderately numerous, echelon formation of pores, and parenchyma are aliform and aliform confluent.

object-73.text: These characteristics match that of BANUYO, *Wallaceodendron celebicum*.

object-74.text: Manong, after inspecting your truck, all the listed species in the permit are verified. You're all clear, and good to go.

object-77.text: Congratulations Sue, for a job well done. You can now take your break.

object-81.text: Now, can you do Sue's job?

object-84.text: Congratulations! You have correctly identified Ipil, *Intsia bijuga*.

object-85.text:
The distinguishing features of Ipil are:

Its orange to dark brown color; moderately numerous and moderately large pores; presence of yellow, red and black deposits; and boundary, paratracheal  aliform, vasicentric, aliform confluent parenchyma.

object-88.text: Congratulations! You have correctly identified Tindalo, *Afzelia rhomboidea*.

object-89.text:
The distinguishing features of Tindalo are:

Its light reddish to wine red in color, pores that are moderately numerous and moderately small, red deposits; and boundary and aliform parenchyma.

object-92.text: Congratulations! You have correctly identified KAMATOG, *Sympetalandra densiflora*.

object-93.text:
The distinguishing features of Kamatog are:

Its reddish to reddish brown color; moderately numerous and moderately large pores; presence of yellow, red and black deposits; and boundary, vasicentric, aliform and aliform confluent.

object-96.text: Congratulations! You have correctly identified MANGIUM, *Acacia mangium*.

object-97.text:
The distinguishing features of Mangium are:

Its whitish or light brown color; moderately numerous small pores that are mostly solitary; presence of red and orange deposits; and boundary and aliform parenchyma.

object-98.text: Did you learn something? Try to identify the following wood species for you to see!
